    <h1> LIVE CITY</h1>

    <p1>
        LiveCity is an API Service which shows information about cities around the world including their
        real time weather update using HTTP requests.
        <div />  This page is a guide for website and mobile developers who want to consume this service.
    </p1>

    <h2>

        Consuming LiveCity API:
    </h2>

    <p2>

        The 2 types of request supported by this service are:
    </p2>

    <h3>
        HTTP GET:
    </h3>

    <p4>
        <div /> The GET requests are intended to return information about the requested city.
        <div />  LiveCity API accepts GET request in the following format:
    </p4>
    <br>
    <br>
    <p5>
        <a href="https://livecityapi.herokuapp.com/api/Toronto&CA">Here's a link!</a>

    </p5>
    <h4>

        Request Parameters:
    </h4>
    <ul class="a">
        <li>City-name: Name of the city to query, with first letter <b>Upper Case</b></li>
        <li>Country-code: Country where the city belongs to, usually the first 2 letters/abbreviation of a country</li>

    </ul>
    <h5>Response:</h5>

    <p6>
        The response will have a 200 (OK) status code for proper requests are made,
        with the JSON result of the following structure:<br /> <br>

    </p6>
    <p7>
    
        <div>
            {"_id": "5a4d3963219a8000004c0deb6",
            "Name": "Toronto",
            "Description": "Best City in Canada",
        </div>
        <div>
            "Area": "3000 sq. km.",
            "Population":"2000000",
            "Attractions":[
            {
            "Place": "Dean Park"
            }

        </div><Div>
            {
            "Place": "Scarborough"
            }
            ]
            },
            {
            "weather_main":"Clouds"
            },
        </Div>
        <div />
        <span style="">
            {
            "weather_description":"scattered clouds"
            },


        </span>

        <div>
            {

            "temperature":"9 degrees Celsius"
            },
            {

            "pressure":"1021 hPA"
            }

        </div>
    </p7>
    <br>
    <h7>
        Decoding the response:
    </h7>

    <ul class="b">
        <li>The response is in the form of a JSON array. The main information about city lies in the value response[0]</li>
        <li>response[0].Name: Name of the city</li>
        <li>response[0].Description: A short description about the city</li>
        <li>response[0].Area: Area of the city in sq. kilometer</li>
        <li>response[0].Name.Attractions[]: An array having the main attractions of that city as a key-value pair object</li>
        <li>response[1].weather_main: Main weather of the city</li>
        <li>response[1].weather_description: A short description about the current weather</li>
        <li>response[1].temperature: The current weatherâ€™s temperature in degree Celsius</li>
        <li>response[1].pressure: The current pressure condition of the city, in hecto Pascals</li>
    </ul>

    <p8>
        <div /> This service only returns main information about a city,
        <div />only if we have the information about that city in our database.
        <div /> Else, it will only return the current weather information.
        <Div />To add information about a city you know, refer the next section
        HTTP POST
</p8>
   <br>
   <br>
    <h8>HTTP POST:</h8>&nbsp;&nbsp;
    <p>


    </p>
    The POST requests to this service are intended to receive information about cities 
    <div/>from clients and to store it in our database.
   <div/> LiveCity API accepts POST request to the following URL:
    <a href="https://livecityapi.herokuapp.com/api/newcity">Here's a link!</a>
    
    
    <br>
    <br>
    <h9>
        <div>POST Parameters:</div>
    </h9>
    <p>
        The data to be posted should be in a JSON format in the following structure:
        &nbsp; <br> <br>
        {"Name": "city name", <br>
        "Description": "Short Description of City" <br>
        "Area ":"numeric area sq km" <br>
        "Population":  "numeric population" <br>
        "Attractions":[{"place -name"},{"Place":"place-name"}]} <br>

    </p>
    <h7>

        Response:
    </h7>
    <p>
        The response will be a status code of 200 (OK)

    </p>
